(1) The Director-General , the Deputy Director-General or any officer of the Commission authorised in writing by the Director-General may investigate any public officer where there are reasonable grounds to believe that such public officer — (a) has abused or misused his office position or authority to obtain property, wealth, advantage or profit directly or indirectly for himself or any other person; (b) maintains a standard of living above that which is commensurate with his present or past official emoluments; (c) is in control or possession of pecuniary resources or property disproportionate to his present or past official emoluments; or (d) is in receipt of the benefit of any services which he may reasonably be suspected of having received corruptly or in circumstances which amount to an offence under this Act.
